From Barron's at 10:30 AM: South Korean memory-chip maker SK Hynix is continuing to reap the benefits of the artificial-intelligence boom. That bodes well for its U.S. rival Micron Technology.K Hynix said sales of HBM products rose more than 70% from the previous quarter and more than quadrupled from the same period last year. SK Hynix and Micron are both producing HBM chips for Nvidia, while their rival Samsung Electronics has struggled to qualify as a supplier for the AI chip maker.SK Hynix is the current leader in HBM chips, with close to 50% market share according to research firm TrendForce. However, Micron is targeting 20%-25% HBM share at some point in 2025, according to analysts at BofA Global Research.For now there looks to be plenty of demand to go around. Micron has already said its HBM capacity is sold out through next year.The South Korean company's message about the wider market for memory chips also looks good for Micron. SK Hynix said the average selling price of both DRAM and NAND chips rose in the mid 10% range compared with the previous quarter. DRAM stands for dynamic random-access memory, which is used in desktop computers and servers, while NAND is flash memory, found in smartphones and solid-state hard drives.Micron shares were up 1.0% in morning trading on Thursday. SK Hynix shares rose 1.1% in local trading in South Korea.

memory and storage components makes it a great stock to buy on the dip. The company just reported better-than-expected financial results for fiscal Q4 (which ended Aug. 29), with strong data center demand sending revenue up 93% year over year.

Increasing demand for Micron's memory chips should continue in calendar 2025, driven by AI, automotive, and data centers. Growth in the AI server market is expected to drive demand for Micron's high-capacity dynamic random access memory (DRAM) modules. Statista projects the AI server market to increase tenfold to $430 billion by 2033, which could fuel strong growth for Micron's data center business.

Other markets are expected to pick up next year. Micron's automotive revenue hit a record in fiscal 2024. The increase in infotainment and driver assistance systems is increasing the number of chips per vehicle. This is a long-term growth opportunity that is expected to drive more demand in the second half of fiscal 2025.

PC and mobile are two more opportunities for growth next year, where Micron is a leading supplier of memory and solid-state storage drives. PC unit volumes are anticipated to accelerate in the second half of the year, driven by upgrades to new AI-powered PCs and Microsoft's discontinued support for older versions of its Windows OS. The release of more AI-enabled smartphones will drive similar demand trends for Micron's mobile business.

I am an AI R&D engineer and technologist since the mid 80's so I've seen it all. I've been waiting for HBM and chiplets for 30 years and I've seen AI paradigms come and go. So I am very happy with what is happening now with nVidia and Micron. But, WD has put itself in the wrong place. The correct model for this current wave of big data LLM based AI is a central repository of data that is tapped into by local fast non-volatile and RAM based parameters and data. Actually there is a new type of RAM needed which is write occasionally-insequence-read-lots-insequence-volatile which will be cheaper in silicon real estate. WD does not win much in this scenario though they will do OK with overall exponential "cheap" data growth i.e. personal data and rarely referred to data. It is the local 2 tiers of fast data that must grow i.e. where Micron is in the sweet spot with inference e.g. HBM.Micron got lucky that OpenAI sparked off this latest craze that should run for a few more years eventually to be replaced by data and compute efficient AI in perhaps 4 years time. But by that time AI apps and use will have grown exponentially to offset compute and memory efficiency. Micron has likely at least until 2030 of demand driven margins and growth before this matures to cyclic revenue. That cyclic model is of course in the bin now so a lot of folks will be wrong footed. And new verticals eg free ranging work bots will proliferate.So, the time to get in is about now. Will be quite volatile.

Piper Sandler: Micron reported a solid quarter, nicely beating street expectations for the reported quarter and the guide for the November quarter, Kumar noted. His core Micron thesis is playing out very well; near-term supply is capped as there are virtually no wafer fab equipment (WFE) supply increases while rising units across various industries and HBM size and demand are putting pressure on the industry and driving up prices, he said. The analyst continues to expect pricing to increase for both DRAM and NAND. On HBM, capacity for 2024 and 2025 is sold out, and Micron is contracted into pricing and units for both years, Kumar said. He noted a multi-design cadence on HBM for Micron and expects the rising demand and limited supply to help his overall thesis. The analyst does not expect meaningful WFE to come on until 2027. As such, he remains constructive on Micron. Kumar projected first-quarter revenue of $8.70 billion and EPS of $1.74.

Wedbush: Micron delivered results that exceeded prior fourth-quarter guidance, Bryson noted. He flagged management guiding towards continued margin growth in the fiscal first and fourth quarters, favorable supply and demand dynamic through calendar 2025, and the HBM demand next year will lift to $25 billion. Net, Bryson found no reason to shift shift his constructive view. Bryson projected first-quarter revenue of $8.72 billion and EPS of $1.74.

Morgan Stanley: Micron posted a strong quarter and outlook, particularly given lower recent expectations, Moore noted. He remained concerned that prices are rising in a slightly oversupplied market. However, as long as producers believe they can sell that product next year, he said it has yet to weigh on pricing.The analyst noted that HBM could continue to deliver a sizeable gross margin premium at equilibrium (particularly given customers prepaying for supply). Interestingly, the upside in the quarter came from the area with the lowest expectations, NAND, as per the analyst. Moore projected first-quarter revenue of $8.70 billion and EPS of $1.76.

Morgan Stanley analyst Joseph Moore maintained Micron with an equal weight and raised the price target from $100 to $114.Wedbush analyst Matt Bryson reiterated Micron with an Outperform and a $140 price target.Piper Sandler analyst Harsh V. Kumar maintained Micron with an Overweight with a $150 price target.Rosenblatt analyst Hans Mosesmann reiterated Micron with a Buy and a $250 price target.Stifel analyst Brian Chin maintained Micron with a Buy and a $135 price target.JP Morgan analyst Harlan Sur reiterated Micron’s Overweight rating and a price target of $180.

“Micron delivered 93% year-over-year revenue growth in fiscal Q4, as robust AI demand drove a strong ramp of our data center DRAM products and our industry-leading high bandwidth memory,” said Micron’s chief executive, Sanjay Mehrotra. “We are entering fiscal 2025 with the best competitive positioning in Micron's history. We forecast record revenue in fiscal Q1 and a substantial revenue record with significantly improved profitability in fiscal 2025,” Mehrotra said.

Last week, three separate analysts from UBS, Susquehanna, and Citigroup each wrote that the current "pause" in DRAM pricing growth was likely temporary. Then on Monday, analysts at JPMorgan Chase noted Micron could go as high as $200 per share, or more than double its current price, if the current up-cycle mirrors the strong 2017-2018 memory boom. Back then, DRAM prices exploded as the cloud computing buildout added a new layer of demand following a 2016 downcycle -- not dissimilar to what HBM and AI are doing today.

CFRA analyst Angelo Zino, who held his $140 price target in place after last night's earnings report, noted the potential upside from Micron's tie-ins with Nvidia processors such as Blackwell and Rubin."We think investors continue to underestimate the content growth story on the DRAM server side, with line of sight for sharply higher HBM growth as Nvidia's Blackwell offering ramps in calendar year 2025/Rubin in calendar year 2026," he said."In addition, we see improved PC/nondata-center demand in calendar year 2025 that will see edge applications include more DRAM memory."Other moves included Morgan Stanley analyst Joseph Moore, who raised his price target on Micron to $114 a share from $100, while Goldman Sachs analyst Toshiya Hari reiterated his $145 price target.

TD Cowen analyst Karl Ackerman noted the PC and smartphone softness, but added that "the anticipated mid-cycle in memory between now and 2025 appears to be shallower than feared, supported by continued strength from datacenter customers."Lifting his Micron price target by $20 to $135 a share, Ackerman added that 'we see stock momentum continuing with B100 qualification, 12H HBM ramp, and improved supply chain visibility in 2025 for PC/mobile as future catalysts."

...artificial intelligence training applications require a new type of DRAM called high-bandwidth memory (HBM). This type of stacked DRAM is harder to produce, and thus carries with it more pricing power.That pricing power may be especially high for Micron, which claims its latest HBM3E product has 30% lower power consumption than competitors. Micron's HBM3E just began shipping in the May quarter, is expected to generate "multiple hundreds of million dollars" in revenue for the August quarter, then "multiple billions of dollars" in the coming fiscal year, according to management. Even better, Micron's HBM is set to have higher margins than Micron's other products, lifting the company's overall margin profile.

MS call is hard to understand because they double downgraded Hynix but maintained Samsung at buy.   Their call rests on 1) Legacy memory is in trouble because of slow sales of mobile and PC. 2). HBM oversupply because Hynix was a monopoly, but Samsung and Micron are entering the market, resulting in oversupply until 2026.  The problem with this analysis is that Samsung is far more exposed to legacy memory (no HBM as of yet).  And if HBM oversupply is the problem until 2026, that makes little sense, because Hynix and Micron have already sold out their planned HBM for 2025.   If HBM oversupply happens, Samsung will be the greatest victim because they have to sell their HBM to no demand.   Customers (NVDA) have already bought all they can use through prior contracts.   2026 will be an issue, but their own call says demand will catch up to supply by 2026.   Doesn't make sense to me.

It is remarkable that this time a death cross print is almost simultaneously by both 50&200 EMA and 50&200 SMA with a lag of just one day. As a rule, I look for a death cross whichever moving average pair print it earlier, as the other pair would be typically too late to the show (it can be 'either or' depending on magnitude of most recent price actions for EMA pair).I would argue that this time both are REMARKABLY late! As a matter of proof, I analyzed RELATIVE slope of MU bear markets with a death cross, versus percentage the price had yet to retreat since the death cross print day until bottomed. There were approx few of them: Nov’14 – Feb’16 ~65%, May’18 – Dec’18 ~32%, Apr’21 – Oct’21 ~12% Jan’22 – Sep’22 ~30% And current Jun’24 – Sep’24. Looking at a relative steepness and rapidness of the June – September decline comparing to past periods, this time both pairs of moving averages are lagging way behind and the death cross is too late to the show to indicate any extra percentage of price decline. i.e. the stock has bottomed and is already in upswing. Status of dram market explained as of now: 1. Yes, MU's HBS is sold out through out 2025. But MU's HBM capacity has never been large enough. I will only make at most 1.5 billion dollars in sales this quarter, whihch is less than 10% of HBM market share. 2. MU's product mix is still mostly in commodity dram such as DDR4/LPDDR4 and DDR5/LPDDR5. However, the pricing trend of these commodity dram has been declining due to: 1) The emergence of Chinese memory maker CXMT is flooding the Chinese DDR4 market with government subsidy. Many Chinese smartphone/PC OEMs receive government subsidy if >25% of their product BOM is procured from Chinese manufacturers. 2) Samsung is "recycling" decomissioned DDR5 modules and selling them at a discounted rate in desperate move to maintain its market share as SK hynix is thriving in HBM/DDR5 yield. I am not kidding go check dramexchange.com and you will witness the downward price trend that has been going on for several weeks now. Only HBM and traditional server DRAM is positive; other smartphone/PC/consumer electronics side is dwindling due to oversupply/weak demand.

I put this out over on the NVDA thread but thought some here might find it of interest.  NVDA is in the enviable position of having far more demand than ability to manufacture the product to meet. Wouldn't you, as a businessperson, love that situation? So now it's how to best manage it. Blackwell, it has been thought, is the future for them. And it very well might be. But the product is a chipset that's almost nightmarishly complex.For a cogent look at the situation, I suggest those interested wander over to the You of Tube and peruse a video put out by Anatasi in Tech. The woman is an engineer and chip designer. Smart. Knows her stuff from what I've observed. Query for a recent video put out entitled "What's wrong with the new NIVIDIA GPU."In a nutshell it comes down to the strata the architecture is being put down on, how everything is designed and how all the various heat effects (by the sub-units) on the overall die are chaotic (my interpretation) and very, VERY, hard to manage. Here is a rundown of policy differences. This is not an endorsement.Mr. Trump recently stated that he supports reducing the top corporate income tax bracketfrom 21% to 15% in order to help companies like MU to compete strongly against foreigncompetitors. 7 years ago, Mr. Trump spearheaded reducing the rate from 35% to 21%.Ms. Harris proposes increasing the top corporate rate from 21% to 28%, a 25% increase inincome tax MU would have to pay instead of investing in it's growth.Mr. Trump wants to maintain the current long-term capital gains tax on sales of MU stockat 15% and 20% for higher earners.Ms. Harris proposes taxing capital gains taxes as ordinary earnings. So an investor in the 28% marginal income tax bracket would see in increase in capital gains taxes on MU stock sales from 15% to 28%, almost doubling the tax owed. Ms. Harris also proposes, with Mr. Biden,to impose the tax on "unrealized" gains, on MU stock that an investor owns but has not yetsold. The unrealized gain tax would be imposed on higher earners.Mr. Trump lowered personal income tax brackets across the board in 2017. Those reductions will "sunset" (end) in 2025 if they are not renewed. Mr. Trump wants to renew them. Ms. Harris avoids the subject, but Mr. Biden has expressed disdain for the 2017 reductions. The increased standard deduction would also sunset. If the brackets sunset and increase to the pre-2017 levels, so too would the cap-gains tax with Harris's proposal.
